TY  - JOUR
AU  - Duggan, J.
AU  - Martinelli, C.
T1  - A Spatial Theory of Media Slant and Voter Choice
PY  - 2011
Y1  - 2011/04/01
DO  - 10.1093/restud/rdq009
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 78
IS  - 2
SP  - 640
EP  - 666
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - We develop a theory of media slant as a systematic filtering of political news that reduces multidimensional politics to the one-dimensional space perceived by voters. Economic and political choices are interdependent in our theory: expected electoral results influence economic choices, and economic choices in turn influence voting behaviour. In a two-candidate election, we show that media favouring the front-runner will focus on issues unlikely to deliver a surprise, while media favouring the underdog will gamble for resurrection. We characterize the socially optimal slant and show that it coincides with the one favoured by the underdog under a variety of circumstances. Balanced media, giving each issue equal coverage, may be worse for voters than partisan media.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdq009
ER  - 



